members.name: MINESHAFT
members.comment: Mineshafts are underground structures which consist of branching mining tunnels with wooden supports and broken rails. They are the only place where cave spider spawners and minecarts with chests can be found naturally.

members.name: VILLAGE
members.comment: Villages are naturally generating structures that form above ground. They are usually generated in desert, plains, taiga, and savanna biomes and are a site for villager spawns, with whom the player can trade.

members.name: NETHER_FORTRESS
members.comment: Nether fortresses are very large complexes that mainly consist of netherbricks. They contain blaze spawners, nether wart farms, and loot chests. They are only generated in the nether dimension.

members.name: STRONGHOLD
members.comment: Strongholds are underground structures that consist of many rooms, libraries, and an end portal room. They can be found using an Material.ENDER_EYE.

members.name: JUNGLE_PYRAMID
members.comment: Jungle pyramids (also known as jungle temples) are found in jungles. They are usually composed of cobblestone and mossy cobblestone. They consist of three floors, with the bottom floor containing treasure chests.

members.name: OCEAN_RUIN
members.comment: Ocean ruins are clusters of many different blocks that generate underwater in ocean biomes (as well as on the surface of beaches). They come in my different variations. The cold variants consist primarily of stone brick, and the warm variants consist of sandstone.

members.name: DESERT_PYRAMID
members.comment: Desert pyramids (also known as desert temples) are found in deserts. They are usually composed of sandstone and stained terracotta.

members.name: IGLOO
members.comment: Igloos are structures that generate in snowy biomes. They consist of the house, as well as a basement.

members.name: SWAMP_HUT
members.comment: Swamp huts (also known as witch huts) generate in swamp biomes and have the ability to spawn witches.

members.name: OCEAN_MONUMENT
members.comment: Ocean monuments are underwater structures. They are usually composed on all three different prismarine types and sea lanterns. They are the only place guardians and elder guardians spawn naturally.

members.name: END_CITY
members.comment: End Cities are tall castle-like structures that generate in the outer island of the End dimension. They consist primarily of end stone bricks, purpur blocks, and end rods. They are the only place where shulkers can be found.

members.name: WOODLAND_MANSION
members.comment: Mansions (also known as woodland mansions) are massive house structures that generate in dark forests, containing a wide variety of rooms. They are the only place where evokers, vindicators, and vexes spawn naturally (but only once)

members.name: BURIED_TREASURE
members.comment: Buried treasure consists of a single chest buried in the beach sand or gravel, with random loot in it.

members.name: SHIPWRECK
members.comment: Shipwrecks are structures that generate on the floor of oceans or beaches. They are made up of wood materials, and contain 1-3 loot chests. They can generate sideways, upside-down, or upright.

members.name: PILLAGER_OUTPOST
members.comment: Pillager outposts may contain crossbows.

members.name: NETHER_FOSSIL
members.comment: Nether fossils.

members.name: RUINED_PORTAL
members.comment: Ruined portal.

members.name: BASTION_REMNANT
members.comment: Bastion remnant.

members.name: getName
members.comment: Get the name of this structure. This is case-sensitive when used in commands.

members.name: getMapIcon
members.comment: Get the MapCursor.Type that this structure can use on maps. If this is null, this structure will not appear on explorer maps.

return: an immutable copy of registered structure types.

name: org.bukkit.StructureType
comment:
This class handles the creation and storage of all structure types for Bukkit. Structure Types are the different kinds of structures that can be generated during world/chunk generation. These include Villages, Mineshafts, Mansions, etc.
The registration of new StructureTypes is case-sensitive.
